The paper deals with the concept of bidirectional relaying in wireless networks and focuses on achieving privacy in the broadcast phase. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the fundamental limits of information transmission and storage. Additionally, the paper involves wireless networks, which suggests that it could also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of computer networks. 

Furthermore, the paper deals with the transmission of confidential information, which suggests that it could belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of cryptographic algorithms and protocols. The paper also involves the concept of perfect secrecy, which suggests that it could belong to the Signal and Image Processing (cs.SI) sub-category, which deals with the processing and analysis of signals and images. Finally, the paper could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category, which deals with the processing and analysis of multimedia data, as wireless networks often involve the transmission of multimedia data.
